You can write the query without the use of `UNION` like this:

    SELECT w.* 
    FROM words w LEFT JOIN glosses g 
    ON w.id = g.word_id 
    WHERE w.word LIKE :searchQuery || &#39;%&#39; OR g.gloss LIKE :searchQuery || &#39;%&#39; 

I assume that `words.id` is the primary key of `words`, so you may need an index for `glosses.word_id`.&lt;br/&gt;
Also you can read [The LIKE Optimization][1] to test and try to optimize the conditions in the `WHERE` clause.&lt;br/&gt;

